The priestess carried Alcippe to an awaiting funeral pyre.  Hippolyte slid off the back of her mare and followed quietly.  She stopped and watched as the young amazon was laid upon the pyre, taking a long solemn breath.  <br>
The priestesses began to chant to Hera and Artemis, and then to Hades.  Hipp's face was stone and frozen.  Her mind a blur as she thought of how this young one had been killed before it was her time.  And in a short battle that would be deamed unworthy a death in the future.  Her honour had been taken away in the blink of an eye, her life taken...trivialized.  And this infuriated Hippolyte.  <br>
Flames had already begun to slowely climb up the funeral pyre.  Hippolyte had not even noticed the priestesses had lit it.  Soon, they began to engulf the amazon.<br>
Hippolyte took a long deep breath. &quot;Herete, young one.  I know your life was honourable.  And I am sure Hera and Artemis do as well.  At least you should have peace in that.&quot;<br>
The priestesses quietly whispered their chants until there was nothing but embers glowing on the pyre.  They quietly left to their temple, leaving Hippolyte still staring at the glow.  She stood there until Apollo began to move his chariot away from the mortal world.  <br>
&quot;Hades, be kind to her soul...please.&quot;<br>
Hippolyte then turned quietly and walked to her mare who had awaited patiently.  She ran her fingers along it's neck, and then poised herself to get on it's back.  She glanced to the embers, &quot;Be at peace, athelfi&quot;  And then hopped on the back of the mare, and rode back to Themiscrya....to home.<br>
